Vanishing of Symplectic Homology and Obstruction to Flexible Fillability

Zhengyi Zhou
Abstract.

For any asymptotically dynamically convex contact manifold Y𝑌Y, we show that S​H∗​(W)=0𝑆subscript𝐻𝑊0SH_{*}(W)=0 is a property independent of the choice of topologically simple (i.e. c1​(W)=0subscript𝑐1𝑊0c_{1}(W)=0 and π1​(Y)→π1​(W)→subscript𝜋1𝑌subscript𝜋1𝑊\pi_{1}(Y)\rightarrow\pi_{1}(W) is injective) Liouville filling W𝑊W. In particular, if Y𝑌Y is the boundary of a flexible Weinstein domain, then any topologically simple Liouville filling W𝑊W has vanishing symplectic homology. As a consequence, we answer a question of Lazarev partially: a contact manifold Y𝑌Y admitting flexible fillings determines the integral cohomology of all the topologically simple Liouville fillings of Y𝑌Y. The vanishing result provides an obstruction to flexible fillability. As an application, we show that all Brieskorn manifolds of dimension ≥5absent5\geq 5 cannot be filled by flexible Weinstein manifolds.

1. Introduction

The study of the topology of fillings of a given contact manifold was initiated by Gromov and Eliashberg in the 1980s. A combination of results in [7, 9] shows that the Weinstein filling of the standard contact 333-sphere (S3,ξs​t​d)superscript𝑆3subscript𝜉𝑠𝑡𝑑(S^{3},\xi_{std}) is unique up to symplectic deformation. In general, one can ask in what case contact manifolds can determine their Liouville fillings. For the topology of the fillings, Eliashberg-Floer-McDuff [14] proved that any Liouville filling of (S2​n−1,ξs​t​d)superscript𝑆2𝑛1subscript𝜉𝑠𝑡𝑑(S^{2n-1},\xi_{std}) is diffeomorphic to D2​nsuperscript𝐷2𝑛D^{2n}. Oancea-Viterbo [17] showed that H∗​(Y)→H∗​(W)→subscript𝐻𝑌subscript𝐻𝑊H_{*}(Y)\to H_{*}(W) is surjective for a simply-connected subcritically-fillable contact manifold Y𝑌Y and any Liouville filling W𝑊W. Barth-Geiges-Zehmisch [2] generalized the Eliashberg-Floer-McDuff theorem to the subcritical case: all Liouville fillings of a simply-connected subcritically-fillable contact manifold are diffeomorphic to each other. Regarding the symplectic topology of fillings, Seidel-Smith [19] proved that any Liouville filling of (S2​n−1,ξs​t​d)superscript𝑆2𝑛1subscript𝜉𝑠𝑡𝑑(S^{2n-1},\xi_{std}) has vanishing symplectic homology, which provides evidence that the filling of (S2​n−1,ξs​t​d)superscript𝑆2𝑛1subscript𝜉𝑠𝑡𝑑(S^{2n-1},\xi_{std}) might be unique. In this note, we more generally consider asymptotically dynamically convex contact manifolds (Definition 2.5) and their topologically simple Liouville fillings (Definition 2.2). We prove the following theorem in §3.

Theorem 1.1.

Let (Y,ξ)𝑌𝜉(Y,\xi) be an asymptotically dynamically convex contact manifold of dimension 2​n−1≥52𝑛152n-1\geq 5. Assume Y𝑌Y has a Liouville filling W𝑊W that is topologically simple (i.e. c1​(W)=0subscript𝑐1𝑊0c_{1}(W)=0 and π1​(Y)→π1​(W)→subscript𝜋1𝑌subscript𝜋1𝑊\pi_{1}(Y)\rightarrow\pi_{1}(W) is injective.) and has S​H∗​(W;ℤ)=0𝑆subscript𝐻𝑊ℤ0SH_{*}(W;\mathbb{Z})=0. Then S​H∗​(W′;ℤ)=0𝑆subscript𝐻superscript𝑊′ℤ0SH_{*}(W^{\prime};\mathbb{Z})=0 for every topologically simple Liouville filling W′superscript𝑊′W^{\prime}.

Note that all the Liouville fillings of (S2​n−1,ξs​t​d)superscript𝑆2𝑛1subscript𝜉𝑠𝑡𝑑(S^{2n-1},\xi_{std}) are diffeomorphic to D2​nsuperscript𝐷2𝑛D^{2n} by [14], hence all Liouville fillings of (S2​n−1,ξs​t​d)superscript𝑆2𝑛1subscript𝜉𝑠𝑡𝑑(S^{2n-1},\xi_{std}) are topologically simple. Since (S2​n−1,ξs​t​d)superscript𝑆2𝑛1subscript𝜉𝑠𝑡𝑑(S^{2n-1},\xi_{std}) is asymptotically dynamically convex and S​H∗​(D2​n;ℤ)=0𝑆subscript𝐻superscript𝐷2𝑛ℤ0SH_{*}(D^{2n};\mathbb{Z})=0 for the standard filling (D2​n,ωs​t​d)superscript𝐷2𝑛subscript𝜔𝑠𝑡𝑑(D^{2n},\omega_{std}). Theorem 1.1 reproves the Seidel-Smith theorem [19].

Recently, Lazarev [13] showed that all flexible fillings of a contact manifold have the same integral cohomology. He also raised the following question.

Problem 1.2 ([13, §8 Problem 1]).

If (Y,ξ)𝑌𝜉(Y,\xi) has a flexible filling W𝑊W, do all Liouville fillings of (Y,ξ)𝑌𝜉(Y,\xi) have the same cohomology as W𝑊W? More generally, do all Liouville fillings of an arbitrary asymptotically dynamically convex (Y,ξ)𝑌𝜉(Y,\xi) have the same cohomology?

Using Theorem 1.1, we answer Question 1.2 partially in the following Corollary.

Corollary 1.3.

Assume the contact manifold (Y,ξ)𝑌𝜉(Y,\xi) has a flexible Weinstein filling W𝑊W and c1​(ξ)=0subscript𝑐1𝜉0c_{1}(\xi)=0. If W′superscript𝑊′W^{\prime} is a topological simple Liouville filling of Y𝑌Y, then S​H∗​(W′;ℤ)=0𝑆subscript𝐻superscript𝑊′ℤ0SH_{*}(W^{\prime};\mathbb{Z})=0 and H∗​(W;ℤ)≅H∗​(W′;ℤ)superscript𝐻𝑊ℤsuperscript𝐻superscript𝑊′ℤH^{*}(W;\mathbb{Z})\cong H^{*}(W^{\prime};\mathbb{Z}).

When (Y,ξ)𝑌𝜉(Y,\xi) has a subcritical filling, Corollary 1.3 shows that all the topological simple Liouville fillings have the same cohomology, which can also be derived from Barth-Geiges-Zehmisch’s result [2]. Barth-Geiges-Zehmisch’s argument uses a foliation by holomorphic curves, while our method is algebraic and uses formal properties of symplectic homology. Moreover, our result is applicable to flexibly fillable contact manifold, which is not necessarily subcritically fillable. The vanishing of the symplectic homology in Corollary 1.3 also provides evidence towards the following question.

Problem 1.4.

If (Y,ξ)𝑌𝜉(Y,\xi) has a flexible filling W𝑊W, is the Liouville filling of Y𝑌Y unique?

Corollary 1.3 also provides an obstruction to fillability by flexible Weinstein domains. We use this to prove that Brieskorn manifolds of dimension greater or equal to 555 cannot be filled by flexible Weinstein domains.

For grading reasons in symplectic homology, we will only consider Liouville domains satisfying the following property.

Definition 2.2.

A Liouville domain W𝑊W is topologically simple iff c1​(W)=0subscript𝑐1𝑊0c_{1}(W)=0 and π1​(∂W)→π1​(W)→subscript𝜋1𝑊subscript𝜋1𝑊\pi_{1}(\partial W)\rightarrow\pi_{1}(W) is injective.

…→π2​(W,Y)→π1​(Y)→π1​(W)→….→…subscript𝜋2𝑊𝑌→subscript𝜋1𝑌→subscript𝜋1𝑊→…\ldots\rightarrow\pi_{2}(W,Y)\rightarrow\pi_{1}(Y)\rightarrow\pi_{1}(W)\rightarrow\ldots.

Given two Liouville domains W,W′𝑊superscript𝑊′W,W^{\prime}, we can join them by adding a 1-handle and then extend the Liouville structure to the handle. The resulting Liouville domain W​♮​W′𝑊♮superscript𝑊′W\natural W^{\prime} is called the boundary connected sum of W𝑊W and W′superscript𝑊′W^{\prime}. The contact boundary ∂(W​♮​W′)𝑊♮superscript𝑊′\partial(W\natural W^{\prime}) is the contact connected sum ∂W​#​∂W′𝑊#superscript𝑊′\partial W\#\partial W^{\prime}; see [5, p.329].

Proposition 2.4.

Let W𝑊W and W′superscript𝑊′W^{\prime} be two topologically simple Liouville domains. Then the boundary connected sum W​♮​W′𝑊♮superscript𝑊′W\natural W^{\prime} is topologically simple.

The following definition is due to Lazarev [13, Definition 3.6], and it generalizes the dynamically convex contact structures studied in [1, 6, 11]. A contact form α𝛼\alpha for the contact structure ξ𝜉\xi is called regular, if all Reeb orbits of α𝛼\alpha are non-degenerate. Let α1,α2subscript𝛼1subscript𝛼2\alpha_{1},\alpha_{2} be contact forms for the same contact structure ξ𝜉\xi. A partial order on the contact forms for a fixed co-oriented contact structure is given by α1≥α2subscript𝛼1subscript𝛼2\alpha_{1}\geq\alpha_{2} iff α1=f​α2subscript𝛼1𝑓subscript𝛼2\alpha_{1}=f\alpha_{2} and f≥1𝑓1f\geq 1; see [13, §3].

Definition 2.5 ([13, Definition 3.6]).

A contact manifold (Y2​n−1,ξ)superscript𝑌2𝑛1𝜉(Y^{2n-1},\xi) is called asymptotically dynamically convex, if there exist non-increasing regular contact forms α1≥α2​…subscript𝛼1subscript𝛼2…\alpha_{1}\geq\alpha_{2}\ldots for ξ𝜉\xi and a sequence of increasing numbers D1<D2<…subscript𝐷1subscript𝐷2…D_{1}<D_{2}<\ldots going to infinity such that every contractible Reeb orbit γ𝛾\gamma of αksubscript𝛼𝑘\alpha_{k} with period smaller than Dksubscript𝐷𝑘D_{k} has the property that μC​Z​(γ)+n−3>0subscript𝜇𝐶𝑍𝛾𝑛30\mu_{CZ}(\gamma)+n-3>0, where μC​Z​(γ)subscript𝜇𝐶𝑍𝛾\mu_{CZ}(\gamma) is the Conley-Zehnder index of the non-degenerate orbit γ𝛾\gamma.

An important fact is that the property of asymptotically dynamically convex is preserved under subcritical surgeries and flexible surgeries [13, Theorem 3.15, 3.17, 3.18]. In this note, we will use the following special case.

Proposition 2.6 ([13, Theorem 3.15]).

Let (Y1,ξ1)subscript𝑌1subscript𝜉1(Y_{1},\xi_{1}), (Y2,ξ2)subscript𝑌2subscript𝜉2(Y_{2},\xi_{2}) be two asymptotically dynamically convex contact manifolds, then the contact connected sum (Y1​#​Y2,ξ1​#​ξ2)subscript𝑌1#subscript𝑌2subscript𝜉1#subscript𝜉2(Y_{1}\#Y_{2},\xi_{1}\#\xi_{2}) is also asymptotically dynamically convex.

Yau [23] showed that contact manifolds admitting subcritical Weinstein fillings are asymptotically dynamically convex. Lazarev generalized that to all the contact manifolds admitting flexible Weinstein fillings.

Proposition 2.7 ([13, Corollary 4.1]).

If (Y,ξ)𝑌𝜉(Y,\xi) has a flexible Weinstein filling, then (Y,ξ)𝑌𝜉(Y,\xi) is asymptotically dynamically convex.

2.2. Symplectic homology and positive symplectic homology

To a Liouville filling (W,λ)𝑊𝜆(W,\lambda) of the contact manifold (Y,ξ)𝑌𝜉(Y,\xi), one can associate the completion (W^,d​λ^)=(W∪Y[1,∞)r×Y,d​λ^)^𝑊d^𝜆subscript𝑌𝑊subscript1𝑟𝑌𝑑^𝜆(\widehat{W},{\rm d}\widehat{\lambda})=(W\cup_{Y}[1,\infty)_{r}\times Y,d\widehat{\lambda}), where λ^=λ^𝜆𝜆\widehat{\lambda}=\lambda on W𝑊W and λ^=r​(λ|Y)^𝜆𝑟evaluated-at𝜆𝑌\widehat{\lambda}=r(\lambda|_{Y}) on [1,∞)r×Ysubscript1𝑟𝑌[1,\infty)_{r}\times Y. For any coefficient ring or field 𝒌𝒌\bm{k}, the symplectic homology S​H∗​(W;𝒌)𝑆subscript𝐻𝑊𝒌SH_{*}(W;\bm{k}) is defined to be the Hamiltonian Floer homology on (W^,d​λ^)^𝑊d^𝜆(\widehat{W},{\rm d}\widehat{\lambda}) for the quadratic Hamiltonian H𝐻H, where H=r2𝐻superscript𝑟2H=r^{2} on the cylindrical end and C2superscript𝐶2C^{2} small on W𝑊W. The chain complex is generated by the contractible Hamiltonian periodic orbits, after a C2superscript𝐶2C^{2} small perturbation of H𝐻H. There are two types of generators: (1) critical points in W𝑊W, (2) periodic orbits in [0,∞)×Y0𝑌[0,\infty)\times Y. One can choose the perturbation carefully such that there is a one-to-one correspondence between Reeb orbits on Y𝑌Y for the contact form λ|Yevaluated-at𝜆𝑌\lambda|_{Y} and pairs of Hamiltonian periodic orbits on [0,∞)×Y0𝑌[0,\infty)\times Y. The differential arises from counting the solutions to the Floer equations; see [4, 19, 13] for details of the construction. The complex generated by the critical points in W𝑊W is a subcomplex and the positive symplectic homology S​H∗+​(W;𝒌)𝑆subscriptsuperscript𝐻𝑊𝒌SH^{+}_{*}(W;\bm{k}) is defined to be the homology of the quotient complex; see [6]. Moreover, we have the following exact triangle.

Proposition 2.8 ([19]).

For a Liouville domain W𝑊W with c1​(W)=0subscript𝑐1𝑊0c_{1}(W)=0, there is an exact triangle:

Since there is a correspondence between the chain complex for S​H∗+​(W;𝒌)𝑆subscriptsuperscript𝐻𝑊𝒌SH^{+}_{*}(W;\bm{k}) and Reeb orbits, one may hope that S​H∗+​(W;𝒌)𝑆subscriptsuperscript𝐻𝑊𝒌SH^{+}_{*}(W;\bm{k}) is an invariant of the contact boundary. Remark 2.11.

Our grading convention of S​H∗​(W;𝐤)𝑆subscript𝐻𝑊𝐤SH_{*}(W;\bm{k}) follows the convention in [3, 6, 13]. Proof of Corollary 1.3.

By Proposition 2.3, W𝑊W is a topologically simple filling. The contact manifold (Y,ξ)𝑌𝜉(Y,\xi) is asymptotically dynamically convex by Proposition 2.7. The flexible Weinstein domain W𝑊W has vanishing symplectic homology by [3]. Then this corollary follows from Theorem 1.1 and Corollary 3.1. ∎

In certain cases, cohomology group determines the diffeomorphism type. One of such examples is a simply connected 555-manifold Y5superscript𝑌5Y^{5} with vanishing second Stiefel-Whitney class considered by Smale in [20]. Smale showed that Y5superscript𝑌5Y^{5} admits a 222-connected filling W6superscript𝑊6W^{6} and W6superscript𝑊6W^{6} is unique up to the boundary connected sum with (S3×S3)\D6\superscript𝑆3superscript𝑆3superscript𝐷6(S^{3}\times S^{3})\backslash D^{6}. Moreover, all 222-connected fillings have handle decompositions with only 00 and 333-handles. In particular, the diffeomorphism type of the 222-connected filling W6superscript𝑊6W^{6} is determined by the cohomology. Since W6superscript𝑊6W^{6} admits an almost complex structure [13, p.4], W6superscript𝑊6W^{6} admits a flexible Weinstein structure and Y5superscript𝑌5Y^{5} admits a contact structure ξ𝜉\xi by [6, Theorem 1.5]. Lazarev [13, Corollary 1.3] proved all 222-connected flexible fillings of (Y5,ξ)superscript𝑌5𝜉(Y^{5},\xi) are diffeomorphic to each other. Using Corollary 1.3, we can strengthen it to all 222-connected Liouville fillings.

Corollary 3.2.

Let (Y5,ξ)superscript𝑌5𝜉(Y^{5},\xi) be a simply-connected contact manifold with a 222-connected flexible Weinstein filling. Then all 222-connected Liouville fillings of (Y5,ξ)superscript𝑌5𝜉(Y^{5},\xi) are diffeomorphic to each other.

Although Theorem 1.1 is stated for asymptotic dynamical convex contact manifold admitting a topological simple Liouville filling with vanishing symplectic homology, the main examples are flexibly fillable contact manifolds. It is not clear to us whether there are other cases where Theorem 1.1 can be applied. However, using Corollary 3.3, we can show the vanishing of symplectic homology for a class of contact manifolds, which might not be flexibly fillable. Murphy-Siegel [16] introduced the concept of subflexible manifolds, i.e. sublevel sets of flexible Weinstein domains and showed that subflexible domains are not necessarily flexible.

    X′superscript𝑋′X^{\prime} has nonvanishing twisted symplectic cohomology [16, §3], hence X′superscript𝑋′X^{\prime} is not flexible.

Corollary 3.5.

Let X𝑋X be a flexible Weinstein domain with dimX≥6dimension𝑋6\dim X\geq 6 and dimX≠8dimension𝑋8\dim X\neq 8 and c1​(X)=0subscript𝑐1𝑋0c_{1}(X)=0. Assume that ∂X𝑋\partial X is simply connected. If F𝐹F is a Liouville filling of ∂X′superscript𝑋′\partial X^{\prime} with c1​(F)=0subscript𝑐1𝐹0c_{1}(F)=0, then S​H∗​(F;ℤ)=0𝑆subscript𝐻𝐹ℤ0SH_{*}(F;\mathbb{Z})=0.

Remark 3.6.

It is not clear whether ∂X′superscript𝑋′\partial X^{\prime} is flexibly fillable. But ∂X′superscript𝑋′\partial X^{\prime} either provides an example of flexibly fillable contact manifold with different Weinstein fillings or is not flexibly fillable but vanishing result still holds.

Corollary 1.3 also provides the following obstruction to the existence of flexible Weinstein fillings.

Corollary 3.7.

Suppose (Y,ξ)𝑌𝜉(Y,\xi) is a contact manifold. If there is a topologically simple Liouville filling W′superscript𝑊′W^{\prime} of Y𝑌Y such that S​H∗​(W′;ℤ)≠0𝑆subscript𝐻superscript𝑊′ℤ0SH_{*}(W^{\prime};\mathbb{Z})\neq 0. then there are no flexible Weinstein fillings for (Y,ξ)𝑌𝜉(Y,\xi).

In particular, if there is a Weinstein filling W′superscript𝑊′W^{\prime} of Y𝑌Y such that S​H∗​(W′;ℤ)≠0𝑆subscript𝐻superscript𝑊′ℤ0SH_{*}(W^{\prime};\mathbb{Z})\neq 0, then there are no flexible Weinstein fillings for (Y,ξ)𝑌𝜉(Y,\xi).

Proof of Corollary 3.7.

Assume otherwise that Y𝑌Y has a flexible Weinstein filling W𝑊W. Then by Corollary 1.3, S​H∗​(W′;ℤ)=0𝑆subscript𝐻superscript𝑊′ℤ0SH_{*}(W^{\prime};\mathbb{Z})=0, which contradicts the condition. ∎
